    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA334-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi iravukkuṟi mukampukkatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante sought the favour of a night tryst.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA334">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>karuviraṉ mantic cemmukap peruṅkiḷai</l>
<l>peruvarai yaṭukkat taruvi yāṭi</l>
<l>yōṅkukaḻai yūcaṟ ṟūṅki vēṅkai</l>
<l>veṟpaṇi naṟuvī kaṟcuṉai yuṟaippak</l>
<l>kalaiyoṭu tiḷaikkum varaiyaka nāṭaṉ</l>
<l>māri niṉṟa vāriru ṇaṭunā</l>
<l>ḷaruvi yaṭukkat toruvē lēnti</l>
<l>miṉṉuvaci viḷakkattu varumeṉi</l>
<l>ṉeṉṉō tōḻinam miṉṉuyir nilaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>          The man from the land inside the mountains,</l>
<l rend="indent">          where the black-fingered female monkey, [her] red-faced big<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">perum kiḷai</term>: here T.V.G. wants to read "relations big in number", which might be more convincing in the context.</note> relations<note place="foot">Either we stick to the given word order, and then we have one absolutive inserted here with a different subject, or we take <term xml:lang="ta">manti</term> as subject also of <term xml:lang="ta">āṭi</term>, but then we have to presume that <term xml:lang="ta">cem mukam perum kiḷai</term> is misplaced to a position after manti, as T.V.G. understands.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">          playing in the waterfall on the side of the big mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent">          hangs on the high bamboo as a swing [and] sports with [its] male,</l>
<l rend="indent2">          so that the mountain-adorning fragrant blossoms of the Vēṅkai tree</l>
<l rend="indent4">          drop into the stony mountain pool,</l>
<l>          if he is coming with the split of lightning for a lamp,</l>
<l rend="indent">          [his] single spear raised on the mountain side with [its] waterfall,</l>
<l rend="indent2">          at midnight in difficult darkness when the showers have stopped<note place="foot">Or: "when he stands in the shower" (cf. KT 161.7: <term xml:lang="ta">māri yāṉaiyiṉ vantu niṉṟaṉaṉē</term>).</note>,</l>
<l>        what, friend, [will be] the state of our sweet life?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
    </text>
